{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"928942b5-52e0-43f5-920e-7ac97700bedd","content":"Based on the skill-validator framework referenced in this repo, here's guidance on both the format and what makes good evaluations:\n\n## Evaluation File Format\n\nEvaluations are defined in a YAML file (typically `evaluation.yml`) placed alongside your skill plugin. Each evaluation is a **turn-based scenario** that tests whether an LLM can correctly use your MCP tools to answer a user question.\n\n```yaml\n# evaluation.yml\nevaluations:\n  - name: search_by_category\n    description: User asks for products in a specific category\n    turns:\n      - user: \"What laptops do you have under $1000?\"\n        expected_tool_calls:\n          - tool: searchProducts\n            arguments:\n              category: \"laptops\"\n              maxPrice: 1000\n        expected_response_contains:\n          - \"laptop\"\n\n  - name: product_details_lookup\n    description: User asks for details about a specific product\n    turns:\n      - user: \"Tell me about the specs for product SKU-12345\"\n        expected_tool_calls:\n          - tool: getProductDetails\n            arguments:\n              sku: \"SKU-12345\"\n```\n\n## What Makes a Good Evaluation Question\n\n**1. Test tool selection** — Can the LLM pick the right tool?\n```yaml\n# Good: ambiguous phrasing that still maps to one tool\n- user: \"Which of your items are on sale right now?\"\n  expected_tool_calls:\n    - tool: getPromotions\n```\n\n**2. Test argument extraction** — Can it parse parameters from natural language?\n```yaml\n# Good: multiple parameters embedded in casual language\n- user: \"Show me red running shoes in size 10\"\n  expected_tool_calls:\n    - tool: searchProducts\n      arguments:\n        color: \"red\"\n        type: \"running shoes\"\n        size: 10\n```\n\n**3. Test multi-turn conversations** — Can it chain tool calls?\n```yaml\n- name: compare_then_recommend\n  turns:\n    - user: \"Compare the two cheapest monitors you sell\"\n      expected_tool_calls:\n        - tool: searchProducts\n          arguments: { category: \"monitors\", sortBy: \"price\", limit: 2 }\n    - user: \"Which one has better reviews?\"\n      expected_tool_calls:\n        - tool: getProductReviews\n```\n\n**4. Test edge cases** — Does it handle ambiguity and missing info?\n```yaml\n# Good: user gives incomplete info, LLM should still call with what it has\n- user: \"Do you have any blue ones?\"  # no category specified\n```\n\n## Tips for Strong Evaluations\n\n| Principle | Example |\n|---|---|\n| **Use natural phrasing** | \"Got anything under fifty bucks?\" not \"Search products maxPrice=50\" |\n| **Mix specificity levels** | Some precise (\"SKU-12345\"), some vague (\"something for my kitchen\") |\n| **Cover all tools** | Every tool your server exposes should appear in at least one evaluation |\n| **Test negative cases** | Queries that should *not* trigger a tool call |\n| **Vary complexity** | Single-tool, multi-tool, and multi-turn scenarios |\n\nStart with 5–10 evaluations covering your core tools, then expand to edge cases. The key insight: **good evaluations mimic how real users actually talk**, not how a developer would phrase an API call.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3408eb0b-bd58-4583-bf94-4f6261ac6bd9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repo is empty and there are no evaluation files to reference. I'll provide guidance based on my knowledge of the skill-validator evaluation format (YAML-based evaluation files used with MCP skill plugins) and general best practices.","outputTokens":864,"requestId":"7FD1:2BC4D4:43BFEBC:4A52068:69F15A7B"},"id":"4907b6d4-6cba-4b53-83c6-cafea2a20f7a","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:10:37.841Z","parentId":"ad97c30d-813d-4eca-b1a8-fb1c7ed2fe87"}
